{
  "doc_id": "13450",
  "text": "Early targeted rehabilitation has been shown to reduce hospital length of stay without an increase in complication rates after THR [CITATION_1] ). Exercise programs beyond the normal postoperative rehabilitation period have been shown to reduce pain and leg stiffness, improve physical function and lessen the chance of accidental falls in THR patients [CITATION_2] . A disadvantage of these programs is the need for patients to exercise under the supervision of professional staff at a hospital or rehabilitation centre [CITATION_3] ). This makes program delivery expensive due to the high costs associated with supervision, treatment and transport [CITATION_4] ). In addition, some THR patients are excluded because difficulties with mobility and transport to a centre exclude participation [CITATION_5] . Studies comparing home-and centre-based rehabilitation programs for THR patients have found no difference in WOMAC scores, complication rates and patient satisfaction after 3 and 12 months of follow up [CITATION_6] .",
